As the year comes to a close, I reflect on how much I recreated myself many times without the care of what society tells me where “I’m supposed to be or be doing” because of my age. I became and became undone many times. And though anxiety visited me throughout the process, I kept joy in my heart because I knew I was becoming someone I wanted to be. ♥️

#joy #reflect #fyp #quotes

Comment 🌱 if this resonates.

If this year has taught me anything, it has been this. 

“Some times it’s not about what you do, but what you choose NOT to do that really changes things for the best.”

This year I engaged less, I participated less, I reacted less. As someone who grew up in survival mode, who is the eldest daughter of undocumented parents, a reaction and action was always expected of me. 

This year was the first year I gave myself the space to not do more than I can only do. I did less in that way yet I gained so much more. 

#quotes #healing #affirmations

The other day I caught myself thinking about the things I have yet to accomplish which made me feel quite shitty about myself. Thoughts of comparison and self sabotaging staging occurring. 

When I have these kinds of moments, I like to ground myself in the gratefulness of the things I do have. I connect to my breath, I give thanks for the food on my table, the warmth of my home and instantly all those things I was thinking about that I “don’t have” or have yet to accomplish don’t matter. 

Striving for more is not bad, but I’ve come to see that “more” is not a cure for feelings of unfulfilledness. “More” happens when we have come to see how much we are now and “more” happens to be an extension of what already is. 🌱

Reminding myself today how hard I’ve worked to get here. ♥️ 

For folks who may be new around here, my name is Kimberly Rodriguez. I am a Mexican illustrator and writer, oldest daughter of once undocumented parents. After working so hard, my siblings and I were able to afford going through the process of obtaining our parents residency five years ago. A long process but happy to be able to see now the ease in my parents sight. 

I was born in San Diego, CA near the Tijuana, MX border. After years of my parents feeling unsafe by all the ICE trucks roaming around, my family and I moved up further up to Northern California.

I started @poetagoddess as a way to heal generational trauma and unlearn behaviors that were brought up by growing up in constant survival. Art and writing have always been a grounding tool for me that has helped me heal and understand myself in a more in depth way. 

I am currently writing a book that will be published by @spiritboundpress in 2024. It is a book that will be filled with personal stories, poetry, incantations, exercises and illustrations that helps the reader through their personal discovery journey. 

Making these kinds of videos always feels very awkward for me but I am learning to celebrate my hard work and get excited that this is something I deserve ♥️ 

Thank you for being here! 🌱 would love to know where you are from and what brings you here.

Kimberly Rodriguez (She/Her)
@poetagoddess is a first-generation Xicana Indigena artist. She weaves her life experiences to the sacred practices of her roots where the sole essence is to embody the magical natures that coexist around us. Kimberly’s art, inclusive of different body types, is rooted in her culture and her decolonizing journey.
​
ABOUT THE BOOK:
Incantations Embodied: Chants and Affirmations for Personal Discovery and Empowerment, is a poetic collection of affirmations, chants, illustrations, exercises and embodiment practices that guide the reader in discovering who they are under the layers of societal or parental expectations, generational trauma and/or life altering events. By building an embodiment practice through the words and exercises offered in Incantations Embodied, the reader will be able to pursue a path of self awareness and reclaim who they are, and define who they wish to be without the limitations placed by harmful experiences or expectations.

This year I am going for what I want. Not waiting for what I want. Living in the threshold of what will come to me will be because of alignment and working towards that which I want. 🌱

This is what life has been lately. Making time for the things that bring me peace. Reading (lots of middle grade books) illustrating new products for amazing brands, spending time with my best friend (my doggy!) smelling flowers, making my desk look as springy as possible!

As someone who grew up in a household where constantly fearing the future was a dominant factor due to unstable income, and my parents undocumentation, I also adopted much of the fear my parents held on to. Fearing the future is not what I want. I want to heal the relationship I have with having to do things that are looked as “productive” or “successful”, or having to prove myself or be someone worth the struggle my parents had to endure. 

I know that by healing the generational trauma I inherited, i am also molding the future of not just myself but the next generation. I get to create something different by embodying that difference. I can both honor my parents journey and also heal that journey by creating a journey of my own that brings me peace and joy. I, we - get to choose that ♥️

If you want to, join me over on my You Tube, I just posted a video about how I am learning to not fear the unknown. I am moving a lot of my content over to making more videos like that. Hope you join me 🫶🏼🌱 

#inspirational #motivational #healing #artist #illustrator #bookstagram

When I think about my inner niña, who never seen with her eyes but with her heart, I always thank her. Thank her for no matter the circumstances, she always choose to give herself a chance. And maybe it was because it seemed there was no other choice but to try - eldest daughter of undocumented parents, what else is there but to try. Even when choosing herself meant putting those before her, because them folk, her papasitos & hermanito & hermanitas were a part of her and wouldn’t it be so lovely to have them see what it looks like to try. What it looks like when the struggle is worth the effort - has always been worth the effort. 

I wrote a book with the best publisher ever @spiritboundpress coming out spring 2024 & I cannot wait for you to read it, feel it, see it, touch it and hopefully you see a little of you in there. ♥️

A huge thank you to @iamjulietdiaz @spiritboundpress & the most amazing editor @jamie_lou_storyteller

We are thrilled to present the cover reveal of "Incantations Embodied" by Kimberly Rodriguez! ( @poetagoddess ) 🌺

This cover speaks volumes about the themes explored in the book, encompassing concepts such as resistance, reclamation, empowerment, magic, healing, and ancestral power.

Kimberly herself illustrated the cover, pouring her heart and soul into capturing the essence of her sacred work and personal story. Her artistic vision, combined with @jillianailsa magic in typography, resulted in a cover that truly embodies the spirit of "Incantations Embodied."

Description: Kimberly Rodriguez, a first-generation Xicana Indigena artist, poet, and activist, invites readers on a transformative journey through her book, Incantations Embodied: Rituals for empowerment, reclamation, and resistance.

Kimberly takes readers on a profound & transformative journey towards self-discovery & empowerment. Within its pages lies a poignant exploration of the human experience, interwoven with elements of spirituality, healing, and personal growth.

At its core, Incantations Embodied serves as a triumphant homecoming—a return to the essence of one's being. It invites readers to embark on a sacred journey, emboldening them to embrace their true selves with unwavering honesty and compassion.

Through Rodriguez's captivating stories, enlightening prose, and enchanting rituals, this book becomes a powerful catalyst for reclaiming our stories, our bodies, our identities, our voices, and ultimately, our power.

In a world where societal norms and expectations often stifle individuality and self-expression, Incantations Embodied stands as a resounding call to break free from these chains. It seeks to dismantle the oppressive narrative that has been ingrained in our collective consciousness, urging us to question and challenge the colonized structures that have kept us disconnected from our own truth.

The book serves as a powerful guide for self-realization, urging individuals to transcend their limitations and embrace their innate potential.

Editor @jamie_lou_storyteller ✨

This thread is a lot y’all, so brace yourselves with me.

I’m in the middle of celebration and grief. Grief for our collective liberation, grief for all the lives lost from the events that have happened over the last weeks. 

Celebration - for the birth of my first book, written and illustrated by me. And this is what has been happening. (read thread) I’m not angry, or upset, as I’ve always had to “prove” myself my whole life. 

I pray for peace, I pray for the liberation of all peoples. I pray that all children get to see the light of tomorrow. ♥️

Huge shoutout to my amazing publisher @spiritboundpress & my editor @jamie_lou_storyteller ♥️ You can pre order my book wherever books are sold or visit the 🔗 in bio.
